WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.030 --> 00:00:03.970
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington, DC.

00:00:22.620 --> 00:00:25.730
&gt;&gt; Anya Creightney: Dawn Lundy
Martin is the author of four books,

00:00:25.730 --> 00:00:30.710
excuse me, "a gathering of matter
a matter of gathering, Discipline,

00:00:30.710 --> 00:00:32.730
Life in a Box Is a Pretty Life;

00:00:32.730 --> 00:00:36.290
and most recently Good
Stock Strange Blood,"

00:00:36.290 --> 00:00:38.880
published this year
by Coffee House Press.

00:00:38.880 --> 00:00:41.170
Dawn received a BA at the
University of Connecticut,

00:00:41.170 --> 00:00:43.590
an MA at San Francisco
State University,

00:00:43.590 --> 00:00:47.410
and a PhD at the University
of Massachusetts, Amherst.

00:00:47.410 --> 00:00:50.800
She's also the coeditor of "The
Fire This Time: Young Activists

00:00:50.800 --> 00:00:54.720
and the New Feminism," and a member
of the Black Took Collaborative,

00:00:54.720 --> 00:00:58.460
a multidisciplinary group
that performs and writes

00:00:58.460 --> 00:01:02.550
in hybrid experimental reports.

00:01:02.550 --> 00:01:13.390
Martin is a professor in
the Department of English

00:01:14.840 --> 00:01:21.810
and the Director for the Center of
African American Poetry and Poetics

00:01:21.810 --> 00:01:26.360
at the University of Pittsburgh.

00:01:26.360 --> 00:01:30.670
Selecting Martin's
manuscript discipline

00:01:30.670 --> 00:01:40.890
for the 2011 Nightboat Books
Poetry Prize, Fanny Howe said,

00:01:40.890 --> 00:01:43.330
"These poems are dense and deep.

00:01:43.330 --> 00:01:46.390
They are necessary
and hot on the eye.

00:01:46.390 --> 00:01:52.680
Discipline is what it took to
write such a potent set of poems."

00:01:52.680 --> 00:01:57.390
It is I think an apt description.

00:01:57.390 --> 00:02:03.250
Though speaking in generality,
I might wager an extension.

00:02:03.250 --> 00:02:07.120
To me, the "I" of Dawn's work
might as well be [inaudible],

00:02:07.120 --> 00:02:11.640 position:56%
a lens totally invested in a nuanced
accurate and interrogated view

00:02:11.640 --> 00:02:15.320
of both Blackness and on a
larger scale [inaudible].

00:02:15.320 --> 00:02:19.930
She is a poet obsessed with
the [inaudible] of words,

00:02:19.930 --> 00:02:25.010 position:56%
both the signifier and signified but
she's also one who loves paradox,

00:02:25.010 --> 00:02:27.610
complication, lineage,
intuitive fragmentary plainness,

00:02:27.610 --> 00:02:28.910
and all things tactile.

00:02:28.910 --> 00:02:30.210
In Dawn Wendy Martin, I find
a brave, dedicated voice.

00:02:30.210 --> 00:02:31.510
She's one who attenuates
the storm only

00:02:31.510 --> 00:02:32.810
to the man we'd notice how
difficult, how caustic,

00:02:32.810 --> 00:02:34.110
how particulate storms can be.

00:02:34.110 --> 00:02:35.410
And it's her intense and strict
instruction to re-circle the poem

00:02:35.410 --> 00:02:36.710
but really the everyday
that makes her so powerful.

00:02:36.710 --> 00:02:38.510
So please, without further
ado, let's welcome Dawn.

00:02:38.510 --> 00:02:41.660
[ Applause ]

00:02:41.660 --> 00:02:43.000
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: Thanks
so much for coming.

00:02:43.000 --> 00:02:44.300
&gt;&gt; Dawn Lundy Martin:
Sure, it's a pleasure.

00:02:44.300 --> 00:02:46.310
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: I had a great
few days reading your work.

00:02:46.310 --> 00:02:51.210
It is really challenging and
eye opening and unsettling.

00:02:51.210 --> 00:02:58.770
Let's start with -- Tell
us about how you -- Sorry.

00:02:58.770 --> 00:03:02.910
Tell us about how you made
space for yourself as a poet,

00:03:02.910 --> 00:03:05.830
how you began to think
of yourself as yes,

00:03:05.830 --> 00:03:10.450
this is something I
can do in this country.

00:03:10.450 --> 00:03:12.940
&gt;&gt; Dawn Lundy Martin: How I
made space for myself as a poet.

00:03:12.940 --> 00:03:21.280
I think that, you know, I've always
been a person who's attracted

00:03:21.280 --> 00:03:22.880
to language.

00:03:22.880 --> 00:03:28.640
I was raised in a household
where my mother read to me

00:03:28.640 --> 00:03:35.480
in a very persistent, consistent
way, whether I wanted it or not.

00:03:35.480 --> 00:03:38.090
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: What sort
of poems were you raised on?

00:03:38.090 --> 00:03:40.520
&gt;&gt; Dawn Lundy Martin: You know, so
I was actually raised on the poems

00:03:40.520 --> 00:03:47.510
of Paul Laurence Dunbar, who's
a 19th century Black writer,

00:03:47.510 --> 00:03:54.830 position:56%
and so he wrote both in conventional
forms, in conventional English

00:03:54.830 --> 00:03:58.080
and he wrote in the
Black vernacular.

00:03:58.080 --> 00:04:01.110
And when I was a kid, those
poems that were written

00:04:01.110 --> 00:04:04.110
in the Black vernacular
were the most exciting to me

00:04:04.110 --> 00:04:05.970
because I thought they
were funny and it was funny

00:04:05.970 --> 00:04:07.810 position:56%
to hear my mother read them because.

00:04:07.810 --> 00:04:11.520
I mean, we'd speak a kind
of vernacular, I guess,

00:04:11.520 --> 00:04:12.920
sometimes in the household.

00:04:12.920 --> 00:04:15.630
It certainly wasn't our kind
of like everyday speech.

00:04:15.630 --> 00:04:21.390
So to have that coming
up under the surface

00:04:21.390 --> 00:04:25.030
of my experience attracted
me to language.

00:04:25.030 --> 00:04:32.540 position:56%
But to make space for myself as a
writer I think was just about trying

00:04:32.540 --> 00:04:40.680
to figure out a way to explore the
world, to make sense of my reality.

00:04:40.680 --> 00:04:45.340
And because I was raised with
literature, it became a kind

00:04:45.340 --> 00:04:49.580 position:56%
of natural inclination to go towards
literature and writing as opposed

00:04:49.580 --> 00:04:54.530
to the visual arts, which I would
love but I can't draw at all.

00:04:54.530 --> 00:05:00.420
If I play Pictionary, all
of my, all of the things

00:05:00.420 --> 00:05:01.720
that I draw are stick figures.

00:05:01.720 --> 00:05:05.220
So it's intensely frustrating
for anyone who's my partner

00:05:05.220 --> 00:05:07.570
because they're like, that's
the same thing you drew before.

00:05:07.570 --> 00:05:11.920
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: So you brought your
own perspectives to your experience

00:05:11.920 --> 00:05:14.960
when you wrote but you also
have to invent your own forms,

00:05:14.960 --> 00:05:18.780
which a lot of other
poets did not have to do.

00:05:18.780 --> 00:05:21.250
They wrote poems that look
like the poems they read.

00:05:21.250 --> 00:05:24.300
You wrote poems that didn't look
anything like what you read.

00:05:24.300 --> 00:05:25.600
&gt;&gt; Dawn Lundy Martin: Right.

00:05:25.600 --> 00:05:26.900
I did once, I did once upon a time.

00:05:26.900 --> 00:05:29.170
I wrote poems that
looked exactly like most

00:05:29.170 --> 00:05:31.730
of the forms that I had read.

00:05:31.730 --> 00:05:36.280
My first series poetry teacher was
Marilyn Nelson [assumed spelling]

00:05:36.280 --> 00:05:39.290
who is a formalist of sorts,
kind of a new formalist.

00:05:39.290 --> 00:05:43.560
And so we were writing in
traditional forms, you know,

00:05:43.560 --> 00:05:49.470 position:56%
villanelles and sonnets and you know
she was really, really instrumental

00:05:49.470 --> 00:05:51.660
in teaching me the kind

00:05:51.660 --> 00:05:56.880
of foundational components
of what makes up a poem.

00:05:56.880 --> 00:06:04.410
And then at some point I
started to get like feel itchy

00:06:04.410 --> 00:06:11.030 position:56%
within those constraints and started
kind of edge my way out of them.

00:06:11.030 --> 00:06:13.930 position:56%
So that's when the invention
started to come but I actually think

00:06:13.930 --> 00:06:19.400
that in order to really innovate,

00:06:19.400 --> 00:06:23.960
one has to know what they're
innovating in response to in a way.

00:06:23.960 --> 00:06:25.260
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: Yes,
I totally agree.

00:06:25.260 --> 00:06:28.020
Yes. And your friend Walt
Whitman and other people

00:06:28.020 --> 00:06:30.390
that were doing expansive
things in the 19th century

00:06:30.390 --> 00:06:33.030
and then the 20th century too.

00:06:33.030 --> 00:06:34.330
But why poetry?

00:06:34.330 --> 00:06:36.730
Why not write essays or fiction?

00:06:36.730 --> 00:06:38.640
&gt;&gt; Dawn Lundy Martin: That's
a really good question.

00:06:38.640 --> 00:06:41.590 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: Because you have a
lot to say, a lot of critical things

00:06:41.590 --> 00:06:45.740
to say, I can easily see you at
home and other forms, other genres.

00:06:45.740 --> 00:06:50.360
&gt;&gt; Dawn Lundy Martin: I do write
essays but my first love is poetry

00:06:50.360 --> 00:06:53.350
and I actually can't say why.

00:06:53.350 --> 00:07:00.110
In some ways as a young person
I was trying to figure out,

00:07:00.110 --> 00:07:04.710
a young person meaning like in
junior high and high school,

00:07:04.710 --> 00:07:13.580
trying to process experiences
that were traumatic and drawn

00:07:13.580 --> 00:07:16.200
for some inexplicable
reason to poetry.

00:07:16.200 --> 00:07:18.900
At that point, by the
time I got to high school,

00:07:18.900 --> 00:07:21.550
it wasn't as if we were
reading poetry in high school.

00:07:21.550 --> 00:07:25.160
It wasn't as if somebody came and
said, oh you should write poems.

00:07:25.160 --> 00:07:28.700
No one told any of
us to write poems.

00:07:28.700 --> 00:07:30.530
At that point it was kind

00:07:30.530 --> 00:07:33.010
of I wasn't listening
to my mother anymore.

00:07:33.010 --> 00:07:36.020
She wasn't reading to me.

00:07:36.020 --> 00:07:41.430
So I think that part
of the reason I was --

00:07:41.430 --> 00:07:44.120 position:56%
I mean, if I kind of look back,
like I don't know what was happening

00:07:44.120 --> 00:07:48.990
in that moment, to kind
of like be a frustrated,

00:07:48.990 --> 00:07:52.670
rebellious 16-year-old
sitting down and writing poems

00:07:52.670 --> 00:07:55.530
when I really wasn't
reading that many poems,

00:07:55.530 --> 00:07:58.050 position:56%
it feels like a strange thing to do.

00:07:58.050 --> 00:08:06.350
But now if I look, I think you know
the language of poetry is a kind

00:08:06.350 --> 00:08:11.290
of terse figuring out and
it may be what I needed

00:08:11.290 --> 00:08:13.030
to survive that particular moment.

00:08:13.030 --> 00:08:18.760
And maybe somehow instinctually
in a way that is beyond me,

00:08:18.760 --> 00:08:26.280
I kind of knew that, but yeah,
it's a difficult question to kind

00:08:26.280 --> 00:08:30.160
of have an absolute answer for it,
to really nail down in that way.

00:08:30.160 --> 00:08:31.460
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: Well,
that's a good answer.

00:08:31.460 --> 00:08:33.300
Identity is perhaps your
most fascinating subject,

00:08:33.300 --> 00:08:36.030
a subject you return
to again and again.

00:08:36.030 --> 00:08:41.230
The I that is me lies forever
in the mute mouth of the image.

00:08:41.230 --> 00:08:44.320
That's a line you can just
think about for a long time.

00:08:44.320 --> 00:08:48.780
This syntax, their syntax,
one definition of this body,

00:08:48.780 --> 00:08:53.680
when the I speaks, it speaks into
another speech and this is labor.

00:08:53.680 --> 00:08:55.780
Talk about that labor of poetry,

00:08:55.780 --> 00:09:00.160
speaking in this other
language, their syntax.

00:09:01.670 --> 00:09:06.530 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Dawn Lundy Martin: I mean, poetry
already, whether it be conventional

00:09:06.530 --> 00:09:10.210
or experimental, whether it
be within a certain tradition

00:09:10.210 --> 00:09:14.480
of poetry is already speaking
a very elliptical language.

00:09:14.480 --> 00:09:20.490
You're telling a story and very
often in a short space and time.

00:09:20.490 --> 00:09:25.170
And so you're making
it, you know, concise.

00:09:25.170 --> 00:09:26.870
You have to take certain leaps.

00:09:26.870 --> 00:09:30.340 position:56%
You have to figure out what to leave
in and what to include in order

00:09:30.340 --> 00:09:34.480
to make that story happen.

00:09:34.480 --> 00:09:43.990 position:56%
The labor of the speaker for the
work that I've been doing is a labor

00:09:43.990 --> 00:09:47.970
to speak a kind of fragmented self.

00:09:47.970 --> 00:09:49.380
That's where it begins.

00:09:49.380 --> 00:09:51.770
And I talked about personal trauma.

00:09:51.770 --> 00:09:58.370
The way that I think about trauma
and the way that I was able

00:09:58.370 --> 00:10:05.590
to process sexual trauma that
happened to me when I was a kid was

00:10:05.590 --> 00:10:12.370 position:56%
through attempting to kind of cohere
myself on the page or something

00:10:12.370 --> 00:10:16.540
and that became like
an impossible task.

00:10:16.540 --> 00:10:18.120
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: Like when
you can't stop doing?

00:10:18.120 --> 00:10:22.160
&gt;&gt; Dawn Lundy Martin: Yes,
it's reiterative in that way.

00:10:22.160 --> 00:10:28.130
One keeps kind of coming back
to this struggle to speak

00:10:28.130 --> 00:10:30.750
or cohere and it's impossible.

00:10:30.750 --> 00:10:36.730
So that's why all of those kind
of stammering around the I,

00:10:36.730 --> 00:10:42.750
the labor of the I, the,
yeah the work that it takes

00:10:42.750 --> 00:10:45.470
to speak one's self begins in that.

00:10:45.470 --> 00:10:49.500
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: You say, every
day it happens or doesn't happen.

00:10:49.500 --> 00:10:53.230
The I struggles to become a
part of the wreaking body.

00:10:54.860 --> 00:10:56.160
&gt;&gt; Dawn Lundy Martin: Yeah.

00:10:56.160 --> 00:10:57.460
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: How do
you know when it happens?

00:10:57.460 --> 00:10:59.980 position:56%
How do you know when the poem works?

00:10:59.980 --> 00:11:02.040
&gt;&gt; Dawn Lundy Martin: How do
I know when the poem works.

00:11:02.040 --> 00:11:03.720
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: How do
you know when it's done?

00:11:03.720 --> 00:11:05.020
&gt;&gt; Dawn Lundy Martin: Yeah.

00:11:05.020 --> 00:11:06.320
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: You could
fiddle with it forever

00:11:06.320 --> 00:11:08.320
and never publish a book.

00:11:08.320 --> 00:11:09.620
&gt;&gt; Dawn Lundy Martin: That's true.

00:11:09.620 --> 00:11:13.190
I don't -- Some people really,
really struggle to kind of figure

00:11:13.190 --> 00:11:16.520
out lie, oh, when is it done
or is this poem like perfect,

00:11:16.520 --> 00:11:18.510
when can put it into the world.

00:11:18.510 --> 00:11:24.080
I'm a little bit opposite,
where I kind of like to put it

00:11:24.080 --> 00:11:26.360
into the world a tiny
bit prematurely.

00:11:26.360 --> 00:11:27.660
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: Nice.

00:11:27.660 --> 00:11:30.440
Read one for us, would you?

00:11:30.440 --> 00:11:32.150
I'll let you get a drink --

00:11:32.150 --> 00:11:35.300
&gt;&gt; Dawn Lundy Martin: I
like the ragged edges.

00:11:35.300 --> 00:11:36.600
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: These?

00:11:36.600 --> 00:11:37.900
&gt;&gt; Dawn Lundy Martin:
No, of the poem.

00:11:37.900 --> 00:11:39.200
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: The poem, oh yes.

00:11:39.200 --> 00:11:40.500
&gt;&gt; Dawn Lundy Martin: Those, too.

00:11:40.500 --> 00:11:41.870
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: This on page 71.

