different in the face.

00:14:41.690 --> 00:14:42.990
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: Very lovely.

00:14:42.990 --> 00:14:47.420
The I is fissure, recklessly
yearning for its whole.

00:14:47.420 --> 00:14:53.450
You seem like a poet who is
fundamentally skeptical of language

00:14:53.450 --> 00:14:55.860
but doesn't have any other choice.

00:14:55.860 --> 00:14:57.160
&gt;&gt; Dawn Lundy Martin: That's true.

00:14:57.160 --> 00:14:58.680
It's it paradox.

00:14:58.680 --> 00:15:00.100
It's a paradox.

00:15:00.100 --> 00:15:02.580
I'm always thinking
about or talking about,

00:15:02.580 --> 00:15:03.880
I talk about it with my students.

00:15:03.880 --> 00:15:06.770
I'm like, okay, we know
that language is flawed.

00:15:06.770 --> 00:15:10.340
We know that language
sometimes doesn't do the thing

00:15:10.340 --> 00:15:12.390
that we need it to do.

00:15:12.390 --> 00:15:16.410
In the example, I -- A very simple
example I give to my students is,

00:15:16.410 --> 00:15:21.190
you know, like if you're having
a fight with your boyfriend

00:15:21.190 --> 00:15:23.670
or girlfriend or significant
other and you're trying

00:15:23.670 --> 00:15:25.950
to convey something to them and
they're trying to convey to you

00:15:25.950 --> 00:15:29.550
and you're just like
desperately trying this

00:15:29.550 --> 00:15:34.320
to make this understanding
happen in language but, you know,

00:15:34.320 --> 00:15:37.540
it's kind of going like this,
like neither person is able

00:15:37.540 --> 00:15:41.020
to really take in the
thing from the other person

00:15:41.020 --> 00:15:42.320
and they're like, oh, yeah, yeah.

00:15:42.320 --> 00:15:43.620
Language isn't working.

00:15:43.620 --> 00:15:48.810
You know, so I am skeptical
of language but then I think

00:15:48.810 --> 00:15:53.930
that in my case it's the
tool that I use in order

00:15:53.930 --> 00:15:56.760
to try to get to something.

00:15:56.760 --> 00:16:00.310
Sometimes I think that
