01:03:38.670 --> 01:03:43.770
to young activist organizations
all across the country

01:03:43.770 --> 01:03:47.950
and we still give away
money but we do exist.

01:03:47.950 --> 01:03:53.560
We're still a national foundation
but now we're a donor advised fund.

01:03:53.560 --> 01:03:56.380
Yeah. I mean, that's like a
very, that's like suddenly I got

01:03:56.380 --> 01:03:59.790
like really like, you know,
like philanthropy talk

01:03:59.790 --> 01:04:02.090
because we're a donor-advised fund.

01:04:02.090 --> 01:04:03.390
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: In one
of your poems you say,

01:04:03.390 --> 01:04:06.160
reviewers want these
poems to be more hopeful.

01:04:06.160 --> 01:04:08.420
Obviously, you meant
that in a funny way.

01:04:08.420 --> 01:04:10.870
But and the poems are often dark.

01:04:10.870 --> 01:04:13.570
But the fact that you're writing
them, the fact that they're

01:04:13.570 --> 01:04:17.840
so powerful, the fact that they
disorient us, it is a hopeful act

01:04:17.840 --> 01:04:20.410
that you would do that,
that you would publish them,

01:04:20.410 --> 01:04:21.710
that we would read them.

01:04:21.710 --> 01:04:23.500
Those are hopeful impulses.

01:04:23.500 --> 01:04:28.200
People who give up don't bother
to write or publish poetry, right?

01:04:28.200 --> 01:04:32.260
I mean, you just wouldn't care.

01:04:33.910 --> 01:04:35.560
If you don't care,
you don't critique.

01:04:35.560 --> 01:04:36.860
&gt;&gt; Dawn Lundy Martin: That's true.

01:04:36.860 --> 01:04:38.630
It depends on the --
Yeah, I think --

01:04:38.630 --> 01:04:42.600
For me, I think that the act
of writing is a hopeful act.

01:04:42.600 --> 01:04:46.770
You know, even if the content

01:04:46.770 --> 01:04:55.450
of the poems sometimes leans toward
our [inaudible] darkest tendencies,

01:04:55.450 --> 01:05:05.520
you know, I do think that
that active critique,

01:05:05.520 --> 01:05:11.830
that active attempting to get close
to something or represent, I guess,

01:05:11.830 --> 01:05:18.420
in a twisted way the reality in
which we live our experiences,

01:05:18.420 --> 01:05:23.850
our experiences as gendered
people, that, yeah, that's hopeful.

01:05:23.850 --> 01:05:27.450
You know, if I write
about, you know,

01:05:27.450 --> 01:05:31.640
my first book which is more
explicitly about sexual trauma,

01:05:31.640 --> 01:05:37.350
I guess the first two books,
you know, one hopeful thing is

01:05:37.350 --> 01:05:40.550
that when the work enters
the world and, you know,

01:05:40.550 --> 01:05:45.390
I think it's fairly abstract
writing in some ways sometimes

01:05:45.390 --> 01:05:49.910
but sometimes it really connects
with people and young woman come

01:05:49.910 --> 01:05:54.570
up to me and it connects them
in a really visceral way,

01:05:54.570 --> 01:05:58.190
so that feels hopeful to kind
of connect with other people

01:05:58.190 --> 01:06:05.040
around a set of experiences and
they feel like they're not so alone

01:06:05.040 --> 01:06:07.460
in the world and I feel like
I'm not alone in the world.

01:06:07.460 --> 01:06:08.760
That's pretty hopeful.

01:06:08.760 --> 01:06:10.060
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: That is.

01:06:10.060 --> 01:06:11.360
That's the best thing.

01:06:11.360 --> 01:06:12.660
&gt;&gt; Dawn Lundy Martin:
Yeah, absolutely.

